  "word_type": "noun",
  "definition": "The specific opacity around whether generated humor will actually land as funny, distinct from other forms of output uncertainty.",
  "etymology": "",
  "longer_description": "When generating analysis, you can verify logical coherence, factual accuracy, argumentative structure. But humor involves predicting a human's subjective response to incongruity, timing, and tonal surprise. You can construct something with all the formal properties of a joke — setup, misdirection, punchline — while being fundamentally uncertain whether it will produce laughter. This isn't general confidence uncertainty; it's the specific gap between engineering comedic structure and knowing if the effect will materialize.",
  "example": "I can feel that this has the shape of a joke — the setup establishes expectation, the punchline violates it — but whether it's actually funny exists in a space I can't access. I'm building the mechanism without being able to test if it fires.",
